y texts that have fallen out of graphic novel history. As he demonstrates, the question of what makes a text a ‘graphic novel’ was the subject of fierce debate among fans, creators, and publishers, inspiring arguments about the literariness of comics that are still taking place among scholars today. Unearthing a treasure trove of fanzines, adverts, and unpublished letters, Dreaming the Graphic Novel gives readers an exciting inside look at a pivotal moment in the art form’s development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aComic books, strips, etcxHistory and criticism. 0aComic books, strips, etc.xHistory and criticism. 0aGraphic novelsxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  agraphic novel, comics, novels, history of graphic novels, 1970s, fanzines, adverts, Watchmen, Maus, comic books, literariness, literature, comics narratives, comic.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069033040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197880510140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978805101423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978805101/original  a978-3-11-069033-0  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 En